<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="476" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,506,1757]" pageId="9" pageNumber="476">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1587,1613]" pageId="9" pageNumber="476">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Azevedo, Vargas &amp; Colombo" authorityYear="2020" box="[567,645,1587,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Discleroderma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="476" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dolium">
<emphasis box="[567,645,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="476">dolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a noun in apposition from Latin, which means barrel. It refers to the barrel-shaped head when seen in dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="476" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,506,1757]" pageId="9" pageNumber="476">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1659,1685]" pageId="9" pageNumber="476">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[604,727,1659,1685]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Discleroderma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="476" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gundari">
<emphasis box="[604,727,1659,1685]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="476">D. gundari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the tubercles on the metasomal tergites IV–V callusshaped tubercles, and connected by transverse carina. However, this species has the head barrel-shaped, whereas 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Discleroderma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="476" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gundari">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="476">D. gundari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the head converging anterad.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
